In C# 12, the spread operator (..) is used inside collection expressions to expand or "spread" the contents of an existing collection into a new one.

ğŸ”¹ Syntax
csharp
Copy
Edit
var numbers1 = [1, 2, 3];
var numbers2 = [..numbers1, 4, 5]; // Expands numbers1 into the new array
ğŸ”¹ Example: Combining Arrays
csharp
Copy
Edit
int[] a = [1, 2];
int[] b = [3, 4];
int[] result = [..a, ..b, 5];
// result = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
ğŸ”¹ Example: With List
csharp
Copy
Edit
List<string> fruits = ["apple", "banana"];
List<string> moreFruits = [..fruits, "orange", "kiwi"];
ğŸ”¹ Example: Mixed Values
csharp
Copy
Edit
var mixed = [10, ..[20, 30], 40];
// mixed = [10, 20, 30, 40]
ğŸ”¹ Rules and Notes
Rule	Description
âœ… Allowed only inside collection expressions (e.g., [1, ..a])	
âœ… Works with arrays, spans, lists, etc.	
âŒ Cannot be used outside a collection expression	
âœ… Can be nested (e.g., [1, ..[..a, 2]])	

ğŸ”¹ Use Case: Merge Lists/Arrays Cleanly
csharp
Copy
Edit
var odds = [1, 3, 5];
var evens = [2, 4, 6];
var allNumbers = [..odds, ..evens]; // [1, 3, 5, 2, 4, 6]
ğŸ”§ Requirements
C# 12

.NET 8 (or a compatible C# 12 compiler)

